{"hypothesis_id": "HD1", "rev": 40, "ts": "2026-05-18T15:40:00Z", "statement": "PERF OPTIMIZATION runner rev4 (multi-GPU) + Modal capability re-check (user-directed 2026-05-18; execution-substrate ONLY, science/architecture/data/objective/schedule UNCHANGED; Tier-0 result final at rev34/rev39; Tier 1 still needs its own pre-registration before any run). MODAL RE-CHECK FINDINGS (installed client 1.4.2 + docs, sourced): (a) nonpreemptible=True exists but is CPU-ONLY (3x price multiplier); ALL Modal GPU workers are preemptible with NO opt-out (2026) -> the rev1/rev2 churn could never have been configured away; rev3 worked because it is preemption-RESILIENT (per-unit Volume checkpoint/resume + ALIVE observability + fewer scheduling units), NOT preemption-free. (b) Multi-GPU in ONE container via gpu='L4:N' (L4/T4/A100/H100/L40S up to 8; A10 up to 4); docs warn >2 GPU/container -> longer scheduling waits. (c) modal.experimental.clustered(size=N) is MULTI-NODE (rank/i6pn, for one distributed model) -- NOT applicable to our embarrassingly-parallel 216 tiny independent units, and still preemptible. DESIGN rev4 (chosen 'multi-GPU 4x'): ONE container gpu='L4:4' (ONE scheduling unit -> NOT the rev1/rev2 multi-container churn class), the 216-unit grid dispatched across the 4 GPUs by a spawn ProcessPoolExecutor with ONE process pinned per GPU (CUDA_VISIBLE_DEVICES set before torch import). KEY: process isolation gives each unit its OWN global RNG, re-seeded per unit EXACTLY as sequential rev3 -> per-unit results are BIT-IDENTICAL to rev3 (the RNG-divergence caveat I raised was DISSOLVED by process isolation -- we get BOTH 4x AND bit-identity; same cudnn-nondeterminism caveat as rev3, not worse). Per-cell standardized arrays shared to workers via /tmp .npy memmap (NO 28GiB packed re-load per worker). ALL rev3 robustness primitives preserved: per-(cell,config,seed) Volume checkpoint + resume-skip, ALIVE-before-import, ~$0 smoke gate (now on the exact L4:4 instance, validates the mu